de, they explore the brightest version of the future of a specific topic =
=E2=80=94 so far entertainment, fusion, and clean energy. The twist is that=
 after exploring this future with a guest, they also prompt ChatGPT to expl=
ore that bright future as well=E2=80=A6and compare how the two match up.
=E2=9C=85 Reid Hoffman podcast (big Masters of Scale fans)
=E2=9C=85 Optimistic storytelling and exploration
=E2=9C=85 Working in ChatGPT into the podcast about the future of entertain=
ment, very meta!
In the episode linked above, Trevor Noah shared his perspective on the rela=
tionship between technology and optimism, saying, =E2=80=9CIn order to be a=
 technologist, you have to be an optimist because you have to believe the f=
uture you=E2=80=99re designing for will exist or you have to believe that w=
hat you=E2=80=99re creating will contribute to that future.=E2=80=9D=20
Amen Trevor.=20
(2) Malleable software in the age of LLMs [ https://substack.com/redirect/e=
60d8aac-0624-43f7-bacc-834a3ae8ee4c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Geoffrey Litt [ https://substack.com/redirect/6bef9edd-c6c6-4580-af0b-=
523d87f600e6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ]
All computer users may soon have the ability to author small bits of code. =
What structural changes does this imply for the production and distribution=
 of software?
Litt explores the implications of LLM on the democratization of software cr=
eation. What happens when everyone, with a little bit (OK, a lot of bit) of=
 help from their friendly LLM assistant, can write code? As Litt views it, =
a more democratic digital landscape in which end-users create and control s=
oftware that fit their specific needs.
LLMs help 'Liberate the Last Mile,=E2=80=9D or the final leg that would-be =
developers need to traverse to execute code. Us normies have all been there=
 =E2=80=94 we have a great idea, maybe even have a bit of technical chops, =
but can=E2=80=99t bridge the gap between insights and actually deploying a =
useful piece of software. Essentially, writing and executing code from end-=
to-end is a lot more complex than it looks, and LLMs represent a step-chang=
e in a normal person=E2=80=99s ability to do so.
As someone who is deeply fascinated by tech, but can=E2=80=99t really code =
(any often gets caught up in the Last Mile when I try), this is a super exc=
iting vision. For top professional developers, I don=E2=80=99t anticipate L=
LMs will make them obsolete, but instead allow them to focus on more and mo=
re complex problems.
(3) Existential risk, AI, and the inevitable turn in human history [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/bd86491c-b40e-4133-8578-894b71769e7d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Tyler Cowen [ https://substack.com/redirect/aac7d8a1-653b-4564-a7fd-301db5b=
9c880?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for Marginal Revolution
I would put it this way.=C2=A0 Our previous stasis, as represented by my #1=
 and #2, is going to end anyway.=C2=A0 We are going to face that radical un=
certainty anyway.=C2=A0 And probably pretty soon.=C2=A0 So there is no =E2=
=80=9Congoing stasis=E2=80=9D option on the table.
This was a big week for the AI safety debate, kicked off by this Marginal R=
evolution post by Tyler Cowen, followed by an open letter [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/aaa7f92d-eaf7-4ed4-8800-d1e574d6d845?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] calling for a 6-month pause t=
o =E2=80=9Cgiant AI experiments=E2=80=9D signed by Elon Musk, Steve Wozniak=
, Max Tegmark, and others, and capped off by an even more extreme call to =
=E2=80=9Cshut it all down=E2=80=9D by Eliezer Yudkowsky in Time [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/90c6635a-cb18-4c51-b1fb-fed03ef1d165?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
How AI is going to impact society =E2=80=94 from how it will impact jobs an=
d meaning to whether it=E2=80=99s going to kill us all =E2=80=94 is an impo=
rtant conversation, and even the AI optimists believe it=E2=80=99s one we s=
hould be having. Sam Altman talked about it on Lex Fridman [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/651854a0-47d0-485b-8dc7-46b02d185bd4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] and Nat Friedman talked abou=
t it on The Lunar Society [ https://substack.com/redirect/d1172c6a-9b94-44a=
1-9da7-6cdcef517b35?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ].=20
When things are moving so fast, and are so uncertain, it=E2=80=99s useful t=
o step back and take the historical perspective, which Cowen did beautifull=
y in his post. He argues that during recent times, most of us have been liv=
ing in a bubble =E2=80=9Coutside of history=E2=80=9D for two main reasons:
American hegemony over much of the world, and relative physical safety for =
Americans.=20
An absence of truly radical technological change.
AI represents the end of #2 (and Ukraine/Taiwan may represent the end of #1=
) and all of a sudden, we=E2=80=99re going to be living inside of =E2=80=9C=
actual =E2=80=98moving=E2=80=99 history. It will panic many of us, disorien=
t the rest of us, and cause great upheavals in our fortunes, both good and =
bad.=E2=80=9D=20
Cowen believes that the good will outweigh the bad, but more centrally to t=
he piece, he argues that whatever happens, our previous stasis is going to =
end anyway and no one =E2=80=94 neither the doomers nor the optimists =E2=
=80=94 knows how it=E2=80=99s going to turn out. In his view, the question =
is no longer =E2=80=9Cgo ahead?=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cgiven that we=
=E2=80=99re going forward with this, what good can we get out of it?=E2=80=
=9D
We can=E2=80=99t change the direction of progress=E2=80=99 arrow; in SlateS=
tarCodex=E2=80=99s words, we are the Puppets and technological progress is =
=E2=80=9Cthe vastest and most formless Vast Formless Thing [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/25c8236f-0f53-4e3f-8a8b-206ff7d4ddd0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] of all.=E2=80=9D We can only=
 fight to make the positive outcomes vastly outweigh the inevitable negativ=
e ones.=20
The closing paragraphs capture our kind of optimism well =E2=80=94 of cours=
e there will be challenges, but we=E2=80=99re here to overcomes=20
Besides, what kind of civilization is it that turns away from the challenge=
 of dealing with more=E2=80=A6intelligence?=C2=A0 That has not the self-con=
fidence to confidently confront a big dose of more intelligence?=C2=A0 Dare=
 I wonder if such societies might not perish under their current watch, wit=
h or without AI?=C2=A0 Do you really want to press the button, giving us th=
at kind of American civilization?
So we should take the plunge.=C2=A0 If someone is obsessively arguing about=
 the details of AI technology today, and the arguments on LessWrong from el=
even years ago, they won=E2=80=99t see this.=C2=A0 Don=E2=80=99t be suckere=
d into taking their bait.=C2=A0 The longer a historical perspective you tak=
e, the more obvious this point will be.=C2=A0 We should take the plunge.=C2=
=A0 We already have taken the plunge.=C2=A0 We designed/tolerated our decen=
tralized society so we could take the plunge.
See you all on the other side.
(4) The Age of Average [ https://substack.com/redirect/6504b2f6-8d60-4659-a=
24d-82cfa3cf5fbb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]
From Alex Murrell [ https://substack.com/redirect/a9d64f3e-41bd-4a11-9b15-f=
232bdef0139?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
I believe that the age of average is the age of opportunity=E2=80=A6So, thi=
s is your call to arms. Whether you=E2=80=99re in film or fashion, media or=
 marketing, architecture, automotive or advertising, it doesn=E2=80=99t mat=
ter. Our visual culture is flatlining and the only cure is creativity. It=
=E2=80=99s time to cast aside conformity. It=E2=80=99s time to exorcise the=
 expected. It=E2=80=99s time to decline the indistinguishable.=20
OK, to be fair, Murrell=E2=80=99s estimation of the world isn=E2=80=99t ove=
rly optimistic=E2=80=A6but unfortunately, appears to be pretty accurate. Th=
e article argues that =E2=80=9Ccreative fields have become dominated and de=
fined by convention and clich=C3=A9=E2=80=9D and this has led to everything=
 looking the same. Airbnbs have the same interior decoration. Coffee shops =
in Copenhagen and Nashville go for the same vibe. Modern brands, regardless=
 of what they are selling, have the same sans serif copy and playful color =
scheme. Even models (see above) all adopt the same =E2=80=9CInstagram Face.=
=E2=80=9D
This is not necessarily a bad thing =E2=80=94 places, things, and people co=
nform to what people like or has proven to be successful. Something starts =
off as new and unique, this attracts attention, and copycats =E2=80=94 real=
izing the best strategy is to copy first, and differentiate later, soon fol=
low. But it does lead to a world, ultimately, in which everything looks the=
 same.
There are two ways to view this:
Everything looks the same; therefore creativity is dead OR
Everything looks the same; therefore there is an opportunity for creativity=
 to thrive.
We tend to subscribe to the latter world view. As more creative work is aid=
ed by AI, we can envision where the sameness issue gets even worse. That me=
ans there will be a growing premium on folks who can produce the different.=
=20
(5) Accelerating Genetic Design [ https://substack.com/redirect/ee90ccd0-9c=
17-4602-8779-bf763509ed0e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/917e43cd-e7cd-4c4c-bb01-ba=
beaa3e37ae?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Century of Biology
(Elliot, a Not Boring Bio Partner, provided a short summary of his recent e=
ssay below, but the whole essay is worth a read!)=20
Biology is rapidly making the transition from a natural science to an engin=
eering discipline. In large part, this is driven by exponential progress in=
 genetic technologies=E2=80=94specifically DNA sequencing and synthesis. To=
gether, these tools can produce massive data sets that make even the =E2=80=
=9Cbig data=E2=80=9D of the Internet Age look small. This opens the door to=
 building powerful predictive models of biological systems using AI. I refe=
r to this paradigm as the 4-S model [ https://substack.com/redirect/f37f077=
5-3d2f-428c-bfaf-58c5862691ce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and it=E2=80=99s poised to dramatically change our=
 relationship with our bodies and our planet.
The main application of this tool stack so far has been to engineer new typ=
es of proteins=E2=80=94which are the molecular machines that make up our bo=
dies. We can rapidly synthesize variations of these molecules and test thei=
r behavior using DNA sequencing. This is pretty cool. Engineering new molec=
ules and proteins has produced new cellular receptors that can convince imm=
une cells to  [ https://substack.com/redirect/846e11af-dc1d-409c-b285-0bce3=
0694e50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
]cure cancer [ https://substack.com/redirect/846e11af-dc1d-409c-b285-0bce30=
694e50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
, and enzymes that power chemical plants [ https://substack.com/redirect/2f=
af83cf-3ccc-471a-a08d-84bc460ba7f9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that produce no waste.
Ultimately, proteins and other molecules are individual parts that are comp=
osed into more complex circuits within cells. A longstanding challenge for =
the field of synthetic biology has been to move up a layer of abstraction a=
nd reliably engineer new genetic circuits. This type of progress would unlo=
ck a future of programmable medicines and materials, where our medicines=E2=
=80=94and maybe someday our clothes, buildings, and physical infrastructure=
=E2=80=94flexibly adapt and compute based on their environment.
In this recent essay, I explain exciting new research from a synthetic biol=
ogy lab at Rice University that aims to accelerate genetic circuit design b=
y leveraging recent advances in DNA sequencing. It=E2=80=99s a great exampl=
e of the promise at the intersection of genetic engineering and AI. Could w=
e someday produce a ChatGPT that speaks the language of cells? Come for the=
 cool Matroyshka doll art, stay for a primer on AI-driven biodesign.
